Length operators 

We have described how to assign to a Riemann surface  two
vector spaces  (for genus 0) 
and  (for arbitrary genus, but ), each 
equipped with a (projective) representation of the mapping class
group. According to the conjecture of H. Verlinde the two 
are equivalent. One possible strategy to prove this conjecture 
is to construct a representation of the Moore-Seiberg groupoid 
on the quantized Teichmuller spaces, allowing one to compare the
respective representations of its generators. 

Length-Twist coordinates 

We find it instructive to discuss the corresponding classical story first.
Regarding the Teichmuller spaces as a collection
of phase-spaces naturally leads one to look for suitable 
Hamiltonians. A natural choice is furnished by the lengths
of geodesics around simple closed curves, considered as functions
on . It is known that the length-functions 
,  associated to non-intersecting  curves
 and  Poisson-commute w.r.t. the Weil-Petersson symplectic form
.
 
In the case of a Riemann surface 
of genus 
with  boundary components it is well-known that there will be a 
collection of  closed geodesics  
such that cutting  along , 
decomposes it into a collection of pants (three-holed spheres). 
The collection of  
lengths  of the geodesics  furnishes a set of functions
on the Teichmuller space  that Poisson-commute 
with each other, . Having half as many commuting
"Hamiltonians" as  we 
thereby recognize the Teichmuller space as a completely 
integrable system. 

A nice feature of the Fock coordinates is that they 
lead to a particularly simple way to 
express the lengths  of simple closed curves 
in terms the variables .
Assume given a 
closed path  on the fat graph homotopic to a
simple closed curve . 
Let the edges ,  be labeled 
according to the order in which they appear on the path , 
and define  to be  if the path turns left(w.r.t.
to the orientation induced by the imbedding of the fat-graph 
into the surface)  
at the vertex
